      <div class="writing1">
        <h>Breaking point: student mental health "in crisis"</h>
        <hr>
        <h9>Ali Ingersoll, Lucas Marchesini and Leia Reid<h9>
        <hr>
        <p>The number of students struggling with mental health has risen and the National Education Union (NEU) says austerity is to blame. “Members have conveyed tragedies that could be prevented by proper government funding," the union wrote in a press release.</p>
        <p>“The chronic underfunding of schools and external mental health services is only making matters worse,” the union’s statement continues. The issue of mental health was one of the main topics discussed at the Union’s conference held in Liverpool earlier this year.</p>
        <p>“The current draconian approach to the education of children and young people is turning our schools into Exam Factories and squeezing the joy and creativity out of the classroom,” said Kevin Courtney, the Joint General Security for the NEU, in a speech he made during the conference.</p>
        <p>According to a survey titled ‘The State of Education’, which was released during the conference, 83% of the 8000 educators who responded report an increase in mental health issues during the last year.</p>
        <img class="sallyPower" src="style/teacher1.jpg"/>
        <p>When asked what prevented teachers from helping students with problems, “there was significant blame apportioned to real-terms funding cuts (57%) in this multi-choice answer, along with a reduction in teaching assistants (51%) and learning support assistants (40%),” points out the NEU in a press release.</p>
        <p>The survey interviewed 8,674 members in England, Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland between 28 March and 3 April 2019. More than half of those who answered (53%) of respondents are classroom teachers and 26% are in head of department or leadership roles.</p>
        <p>A spokesperson for the Department for Education (DfE), said by email and published in a press release that children’s mental health is a “key priority” and the new compulsory health education curriculum will ensure children are taught “how to look after their mental wellbeing and recognise when classmates are struggling.”</p>
        <p>The DfE is reportedly investing more money into mental health support and says, by the 2023-2024 school year, they’ll be spending an additional £2.3bn annually.</p>
        <p>Professor Sally Power, co-director of Wales Institute of Social and Economics Data and Method (WISERD) and a governor of two schools, agrees that mental health is a huge issue in the educational system.</p>
        <p>The education researcher feels this puts extra pressure on schools in a moment when budgets are being squeezed. Power says, around a decade or two ago, teachers weren’t required to act as mental health counselors in addition to juggling their daily tasks. “There weren’t the expectations that schools would be dealing with students mental health issues at the level that they’re expected to now,” she explains.</p>
        <p>“Teachers are having to pick up slack on things they haven’t been qualified for so they’re deeply stressed themselves about this,” said Mary O’Hara, the author of ‘Austerity Bites.’</p>
        <p>O’Hara says the issues many students face now are a fallout from austerity cuts to other welfare programs and she feels, those issues are perpetuated farther by requesting teachers fill the gap left by the deficit.</p>
        <p>“If you are a teacher, you want to be able to respond to your pupils needs and in the best way possible but you also know that this is an area that requires professional intervention and early intervention and a lot of the things that were cut by austerity were early intervention bits,” she adds.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="writing1">
        <h>From north to south and nine years time – a reflection on the differences in school resources</h>
        <hr>
        <h9>Ali Ingersoll</h9>
        <hr>
        <p>Zippers zip, notebook covers slap shut, and trainers shuffle out of the classroom as postgraduate students leave for the day. Among them is Laura Ellen Edwards. The 26-year-old attending Cardiff University is from Conwy.</p>
        <p>She describes her town as “better off than most” in North Wales.</p>
        <p>“I am from there, I love it there,” said Edwards, who, loves it so much, she aims to return home to visit her family at least twice each month.</p>
        <p>The postgrad student attended Bangor University then moved to Cardiff to receive her postgraduate certificate in education. She says, while she loves North Wales, she feels opportunities are limited there and she had to move to launch her career.</p>
        <p>“Young people are leaving North Wales and they’re leaving Wales, in general. But I’m lucky I even had this opportunity,” said Edwards while she reflected on her education in Conwy.</p>
        <p>She refers to Cardiff as a “utopia” and believes the city gives outsiders a “false sense of what Wales is like.” She says the deprivation around the country, especially in areas like the valleys and North Wales, is far greater than what’s seen in the capital city.</p>
        <p>According to data from the Stats Wales, Cardiff schools are receiving £1.966 million less now in real terms than they were prior to austerity. Meanwhile, Conwy schools difference is more than £6.5 million less in real terms.</p>
        <p>“It’s mad. When you actually start thinking about it, it’s terrifying.”</p>
        <p>Edwards believes she has been set up better than most students though. While receiving her PGCE, Edwards did her training at Merthyr Tydfil Coleg, a school in a region receiving around £4.3 million less in funding now than prior to austerity, per StatsWales.</p>
        <p>“They grew up under these cuts,” said Edwards when asked why she thinks, despite the data showing the North Wales community being impacted more, she thought the Brecon Beacons region school was hit harder. She feels consistently slashing funds has led schools to have to make do with what they have. During her teaching year, Edwards taught creative media in Merthyr Tydfil and says the equipment students were required to learn on was outdated. According to Edwards, students were still burning videos onto DVDs and didn’t have the capability to upload to sites, like YouTube. She says the rooms were too small to accommodate all the teens enrolled and there were only two computers for the 25 students.</p>
        <p>“It hits hard across the board,” said Edwards. “In Conwy, it wasn’t this bad. It’s making me think now. Wow, it really has changed. I don’t like to think about it but it has changed. Younger people don’t have what I had. I am very lucky.”</p>
      </div>
    </div>
