          <div class = "writing1">
            <h>School funding discrepancies shine spotlight on U.K.'s social mobility issues</h>
            <hr>
            <h9>Ali Ingersoll</h9>
            <hr>
            <p>Laura Ellen Edwards spends hours in the Cardiff University library, writing essays, researching the media. The 26-year-old is a postgraduate student getting her masters degree in digital media and society.</p>
            <p>Edwards, from Conwy, grew up in what she describes as a modest home. Her parents met at Sheffield where they received high end national diplomas in business and finance.</p>
            <p>“We’re very lucky, compared to most in north Wales,” said Edwards during an interview.</p>
            <p>Edwards says she often talks about her upbringing but only recently started reflecting on the opportunities she has had. In 2016, she moved to Cardiff from the Snowdonia-area village to be with her partner. She says, financially, she was only able to move because her partner’s family is based in the capital so she had a place to live and didn’t have to save money for an initial deposit on a flat. She says, when she moved to south Wales, she saw all the opportunities here – opportunities she says she and others in the north aren’t afforded.</p>
            <p>The Cardiff University postgraduate student feels education is a priority for many young people all over the country but feels, some students in areas which have been defunded, might not realize their potential or the opportunities available to them.</p>
            <img class="laura" src="style/laura.jpg" width="480" alt="Laura Ellen Edwards, a postgraduate student, questions social mobility prospects after discussing impacts of austerity" title="Postgraduate student"/>
            <p>“I think it’s a down fall of the U.K.,” said Edwards. “London takes all the money and sometimes politicians don’t concentrate anywhere else but London.”</p>
            <p>London-based schools makes up 12% of the schools in England and receive 15% of funding, a rate which isn’t noticeably disproportionate. However, education research expert, Professor Sally Power from Cardiff University, found upper and middle-class families are more willing to make up for the short-fallings in their children’s schools and they’ll donate to the school, which she says disenfranchises students who are from disadvantaged families.</p>
            <p>Edwards, a future teacher, feels, overall, students in school now have more opportunities but worries the concentration of funding and wealth in urban areas decreases social mobility and marginalizes people born into working-class and poverty-stricken families. She believes she and other millennials are in better positions than their parents but feels uncertain about the kids who are growing up now.</p>
            <p>“Our generation is 100% better set up,” says Edwards. “There are more opportunities, more choices of courses for people to get into that they’re interested in. But if they’ll be able to get a job with that certification, I don’t know. We could have more opportunities but if the jobs aren’t there, they can’t get a job.”</p>
            <p>This reality came to light again recently when Edwards’ brother, who has a law degree, settled for a job as Tesco truck driver.</p>
            <p>“Even if he wanted to be a lawyer right now, he couldn’t because there aren’t law firms in our town,” said Edwards.</p>
            <p>Edwards says her dad, whose certification is equivalent to a level-5 schooling completion, makes more than £50,000 annually, a figure she says she cannot imagine making. On top of not being able to achieve that sort of financial stability, the postgraduate student is paying off debt connected to money she had to borrow for her postgraduate teaching certificate and master’s degree. She is hopeful she’ll be able to pay off the money she borrowed in the next 15 years. She says, even if that limits how much money she can save and spend, she feels it was necessary to take out the money for her education and future.</p>
            <p>“The most terrifying thing is- imagine if you didn't have the qualification,” said Edwards. “What is the hope for the people who can't afford the education? If you didn't have that, the loans, the ability to get degrees - where would you be?”</p>
            <p>While Edwards doesn’t have that answer, experts in the field believe that’s the issue the country is facing right now. According to the House of Lords Social Mobility committee’s annual report, 80% of those who are born in well-off backgrounds are more likely to wind up in a professional setting than those who are not born into similar advantages. The committee reports the mobility prospects have sat stagnant for the last four years.</p>
            <p>“Austerity doesn’t help with social mobility but [there are] complex reasons for [social mobility] and especially over the last 40 years,” said Mary O’Hara, a journalist and author of ‘Austerity Bites.’ “Austerity might have a role in that but there are much wider cultural and economic factors in play there.”</p>
            <p>Edwards, who did not grow up in the age of austerity, says, while appreciative of her upbringing and the lifestyle her parents have worked to afford her, she feels slightly guilty those opportunities are not available to all.</p>
            <p>“I’m very lucky,” she said, looking down the hallway, as if she’s simultaneously looking at her past and future. “I know I’m lucky.”</p>
          </div>

