        <div id="schools" class="details">
          <div class=writing1>
            <h>Austerity spending cuts impacting all in the classroom</h>
            <hr>
            <h9>Lucas Marchesini</h9>
            <hr>
            <p>Catalina Silva relaxes on a Sunday evening before she’ll head back to work at a school as a replacement teacher in Cardiff. There, she has seen firsthand the impact of diminishing budgets for schools. “Teachers have a limit of 300 photocopies per year. This is nothing in a class with 30 students,” she said.</p>
            <p>“Because of that, the kids spend a lot of time copying something instead of doing exercises and learning”, she adds. Silva feels this harms the quality of education. “Time is the biggest issue. Because of things like that, they do not have enough time for other activities required in the curriculum.”</p>
            <img class="cataPic" src="style/cata.jpg" alt="Teachers experiencing funding shortage in classroom" title="Teachers experiencing funding shortage in classroom"/>
            <p>The decreased financial support has increased pressure on teachers and Silva says, it’s leading to educators having to band together to fundraise for classroom materials. As she explains, each teacher has a quota for the year and when it is reached, somebody must chip in to fill the gap. To avoid disruption in the classroom, teachers end up doing it.</p>
            <p>What Silva has witnessed is far from the exception. A survey from the National Education Union (NEU) released last year revealed that more than three quarters of interviewed teachers saw cuts in classroom material in 2017.</p>
            <p>The most recent spending analysis for Welsh and English schools comes from the 2017-2018 school year and reveals, since the beginning of austerity, the majority of schools in Wales - 1299 of the 1451 - have decreased their budgetary allocations per pupil. Additionally, 73% of schools in England have also reduced spending per pupil.</p>
            <p>The spending information for England is more in depth, with categories breaking down how the funding has changed for teachers, allowing us to evaluate the discrepancies throughout austerity. More than 10,000 schools provided this information to the Department for Education (DfE). Our reporting reveals, on average, staff funding has decreased by more than 20% since the inception of austerity. In 2017-2018, spending for English teaching staff sat at £2,597.02 per pupil, which is £587.76 per pupil less than it was during 2009-2010.</p>
            <p>All 13,336 English schools released financial information for spending on supply teachers, like Silva. The average amount spent per student in 2017-2018 is £142.75, which is £37.68 less than they spent prior to austerity.</p>
            <p>Silva believes parents who are financially able should pitch in with purchasing necessary school materials as she believes having more time to spend focusing on the curriculum will only benefit the children she’s tasked with teaching.</p>
          </div>
          <div class= "writing1">
            <h>Prospective teachers fearful about the future of education</h>
            <hr>
            <h9>Ali Ingersoll</h9>
            <hr>
            <p>The sun reflects off the sides of the glass building in downtown Cardiff during an unseasonably warm April afternoon in Wales. Laura Ellen Edwards sits on her laptop, endlessly searching for teaching jobs. The postgraduate student is fearful about her future.</p>
            <p>“Every public service is hammered down,” said Edwards. “Education gets an absolute hammering.”</p>
            <p>She’s been in this position before though, when she failed her A-levels.</p>
            <p>“I had a rough time as a student and I didn’t want to be in school anymore.”</p>
            <p>That all changed though when she started attending Coleg Llandrillo for media studies, an opportunity she describes as a “second chance that changed my life.” During her time in college, Edwards says she connected with her teachers in a way she hadn’t before. She describes one lecturer, Chris, as her “role model” and says the relationship she had with him inspired her to pursue a career in education.</p>
            <p>“I want to [be a teacher] because I know there are probably a few kids out there who think school isn’t for them and I want to teach them that, if maths and science isn’t your thing, you can do something else.”</p>
            <p>Edwards recently received her postgraduate certificate in education, completing her trainee teaching program during the 2017-2018 schools year. She says many teachers have zero hour contracts – a type of contract where employers aren’t obliged to provide minimum working hours. Edwards says one of her friends from her PGCE program, who is a single mom, landed a teaching job upon graduation but is only getting four hours right now and struggling to make ends meet.</p>
            <p>“The way education is now, it’s as if [employers] want it be like a hobby or something you do after your career. You can’t make a living off of the hours and wages,” said Edwards.</p>
            <p>With these zero contract hours, teachers are only paid for the work they put in in the classroom so four hours of teaching means four hours of pay. According to Edwards, for a teacher to make the most of those four hours for the students, they’d have to put in around ten hours of lesson planning; ten hours which would be unpaid. Edwards feels these types of contracts and the stress they put on teachers impacts the students in the classroom and, because of the lack of funding, it’s leading to a shortage in educators.</p>
            <p>Despite knowing that, she’s hopeful she can land a full-time job at a college, as that’s where she feels there’s the greatest need for dedicated teachers.</p>
            <p>“I still really want to [teach]. I think I can make a difference so I’m going to try.”</p>
          </div>
        </div>


      <div id='data' class="details">
        <h2>Data and Methodology</h2>
        <p>The data used in this investigation has two main sources: <a href="https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/download-data"> the Department for Education</a> (DfE) when it comes to English schools and <a href="https://statswales.gov.wales/Catalogue/Local-Government/Finance/Revenue/Delegated-School-Budgets/delegatedschoolbudgets-by-school"> StatWales </a> for information about Wales. In both cases, the information was separated by school.</p>
        <p>To measure the effects of austerity on spending per pupil per school in the two countries, the data was clustered in two periods: the 8 years of Austerity, starting with the first budget of David Cameron government (2010-2011) to the last Tory administration with available data (2017-2018).</p>
        <p>The eight year period was compared to one timeframe with the same extension ending in 2009-2010 and starting in 2002-2003.</p>
        <p>All values were adjusted by the inflation in the period according to the Office of National Statistics (ONS) of 58.48% (CPS).</p>
        <p>An important methodology information regarding the spending per pupil by ethnicity is that masked data of the number of pupils of a specific ethnicity was replaced by 1 when required.</p>
        <p>This happened because the DfE masks the number of pupils of a ethnicity in a school when there are only one or two of that ethnicity in the establishment. The same procedure was applied to Wales data.</p>
      </div>
